[1] Uganda
Date: 10 Jun 2002 16:29
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: New Vision/All Africa Global Media via COMTEX [10 Jun 2002 16:29]

Cholera Hits Kabarole
----------------
There is an outbreak of cholera in Kabarole district, the district
health department has confirmed. The District Director of Health
Services, Dr. Kabagambe Rugamba recently said at least 2 cases had
been confirmed at Buhinga Government referral hospital. It was
reported that 1 of the victims died.
Rugamba said another 28 suspected cases were reported last month. He
said affected areas included Kagote and Njara in Fort Portal
municipality and Harugongo in Burahya county. One family was said to
have had as many as 5 victims admitted.
"We are trying to see whether we can get some assistance from the
ministry (health), especially intravenous fluids and tents," he said,
"the hospital lacked an isolation ward so temporary shelters were
needed."
[by Emmanuel Mulondo ]
******
[2] Somalia
Date: 14 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Radio Banaadir, Mogadishu via BBC Monitoring International
Reports [edited]

29 cholera victims recovering at Mogadishu hospital
-------------------------------------------------------
On 14 May 2002, 29 people suffering from cholera were admitted in 24
hours to Mogadishu's Habeb Hospital. The patients, brought from
Mogadishu and its surroundings, were reportedly in a stable condition
after receiving treatment.
Speaking to Radio Banaadir reporter Abdisalan His, the hospital's
deputy administrator, Hasan Muse (last name indistinct), said cholera
cases had been on the rise among the Somali population and appealed
for joint efforts to curb the disease. Mr Muse clarified that the
hospital was being assisted in the fight against the disease by
Al-Muntada (Islamic charity) organization.
******
